<UserControl x:Class="RodentVRSettings.Views.MouseInputView"
             xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml/presentation"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml"
             xmlns:mc="http://schemas.openxmlformats.org/markup-compatibility/2006" 
             xmlns:d="http://schemas.microsoft.com/expression/blend/2008" 
             xmlns:local="clr-namespace:RodentVRSettings.Views"
			 xmlns:controls="http://metro.mahapps.com/winfx/xaml/controls"
			 mc:Ignorable="d" 
             d:DesignHeight="450" d:DesignWidth="800">
	<StackPanel Orientation="Vertical">
		<TextBlock Style="{StaticResource Description}">
			Movement input for the RodentVR simulation is received through two mice plugged into the computer.
			The mice are positioned so as to touch the equator of the ball that the rodent walks on, with one 
			mouse behind the rodent and the other to the right of the rodent. The mouse behind the rodent measures
			the rodent's forward and backward movement, while the mouse on the side measures the rodent's orientation.
			<LineBreak/>
			Since multiple computer mice are used as input, RodentVR needs to be told which computer mouse is placed
			behind the rodent and which is placed to its side.
			<LineBreak/>
			<LineBreak/>
			To record which computer mouse is positioned behind the rodent and which is to its side, click the buttons
			below with the correct mice. The mouse's name will be displayed in the text box to the side of the button.
		</TextBlock>
		<Label Content="Behind Mouse Device Name" />
		<TextBlock Style="{StaticResource Description}">
			The mouse that is positioned behind the rodent.
		</TextBlock>
		<StackPanel Orientation="Horizontal">
			<TextBox Name="tbMouseADeviceName" Style="{StaticResource textbox}" Grid.Column="0" TextChanged="tbMouseADeviceName_TextChanged" />
			<Button Name="bttnMouseA" Click="bttnMouse_Click" Margin="4,0,0,10" Content="Click with Behind Mouse"/>
		</StackPanel>
		<Label Content="Behind Mouse Multiplier" />
		<TextBlock Style="{StaticResource Description}">
			How much to move RodentVR simulation forward when the rodent rolls the ball forward.
		</TextBlock>
		<controls:NumericUpDown Name="nudMouseAMultiplier" ValueChanged="nudMouseAMultiplier_ValueChanged" Minimum="-100" Maximum="100" HasDecimals="True" Interval="0.0025" StringFormat="N4" HorizontalAlignment="Left" />
		<Label Content="Side Mouse Device Name" />
		<TextBlock Style="{StaticResource Description}">
			The mouse that is positioned to the right of the rodent.
		</TextBlock>
		<StackPanel Orientation="Horizontal">
			<TextBox Name="tbMouseBDeviceName" Style="{StaticResource textbox}" TextChanged="tbMouseBDeviceName_TextChanged"/>
			<Button Name="bttnMouseB" Click="bttnMouse_Click" Margin="4,0,0,10" Content="Click with Side Mouse"/>
		</StackPanel>
		<Label Content="Side Mouse Multiplier" />
		<TextBlock Style="{StaticResource Description}">
			How much to rotate the RodentVR simulation when the rodent rolls the ball sideways.
		</TextBlock>
		<controls:NumericUpDown Name="nudMouseBMultiplier" ValueChanged="nudMouseBMultiplier_ValueChanged" Minimum="-100" Maximum="100" HasDecimals="True" Interval="0.0025" StringFormat="N4" HorizontalAlignment="Left"  />
		<Separator Background="Transparent" Height="50"/>
		<TextBlock xml:space="preserve" Style="{StaticResource Description}">To manually find the computer mouse's Device Name, follow these steps:
    1. Open Windows' Device Manager.
    2. Click 'Mice and other pointing devices'.
    3. Find the correct computer mouse in the list (it helps to unplug the other mice).
    4. Right-click on the correct mouse and select 'Properties'.
    5. Click on the 'Details' tab page.
    6. In the 'Property' dropdown select 'Device instance path'.
    7. Right-click copy the 'Value' and paste it into the 'Device Name' text box.
		</TextBlock>
	</StackPanel>
</UserControl>
